,"South Molton, Devon, England":"South Molton, Devon, England","Bostock, Cheshire, England":"Bostock, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moulton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Cheshire and Lancashire): habitational name from one or more of the places called Moulton (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire, Suffolk, North Yorkshire), most of which are named with the Old English personal name <i>Mūl(a)</i>, the Old Norse personal name <i>Múli</i>, or Old English <i>mūl</i> ‘mule’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Molden","meanings":["English:","metronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Mold</i>, a form of <i>Maud</i>, with the characteristically West Midland genitival suffix <i>-en</i>.","variant of   Moulton  ."]},{"name":"Moulden","meanings":["English: variant of   Moulton  ."]},{"name":"Molton","meanings":["English: variant of   Moulton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":43,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Moulton was born in 1339, in Moulton, Cheshire, England, his father, William de Moulton, was 56 and his mother, Joan de Latham, was 53. He had at least 1 son with Joan De Skinton. He died in 1396, in Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1339–1396":"1339–1396","1312–1383":"1312–1383","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1335–1429":"1335–1429","1360–1384":"1360–1384","1284–1365":"1284–1365","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1396":"1396","1286":"1286","1384":"1384","1284":"1284","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1326":"1326","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1 June 1365":"1. juuni 1365","1365":"1365","1429":"1429","1319":"1319","1339":"1339","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Moulton, Cheshire, England":"Moulton, Cheshire, England","England":"England","South Molton, Devon, England":"South Molton, Devon, England","Bostock, Cheshire, England":"Bostock, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1339–1396":"1339–1396","1312–1383":"1312–1383","1319–Male":"1319–Kuollut","1326–Female":"1326–Kuollut","1335–1429":"1335–1429","1360–1384":"1360–1384","1284–1365":"1284–1365","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","about 1360":"noin 1360","1396":"1396","1286":"1286","1384":"1384","1284":"1284","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1326":"1326","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1 June 1365":"1. kesäkuuta 1365","1365":"1365","1429":"1429","1319